    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2713433950" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2713433950" />
    <a title="Zitong Ren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77983193-zitong-ren"><img alt="Zitong Ren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1552188473p2/77983193.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2713433950?book_show_action=true">Sep 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zitong Ren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zitong Ren" href="/user/show/77983193-zitong-ren">Zitong Ren</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/77983193-zitong-ren?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/77983193-zitong-ren?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/77983193-zitong-ren?shelf=ewwwwww">ewwwwww</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2713433950" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17269285727826228318">I tried to read this book and actually hoped that I would like it, yeah, nah. I got up to page 42 and was like <i>there are better books out there than me slogging through the next 700 pages and can use my time better doing anything else</i>. So that’s what I did and dropped this book entirely. <br/><br/>I first heard about this book when I picked up <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/79203.Spangle' title='Spangle by Gary Jennings' rel='nofollow noopener'> Spangle</a> earlier this year and ended up really liking it and saw that the author had a much more popular book out there called Aztec. This was that book. I’m not gi</span>
  <span id="freeText17269285727826228318" style="display:none">I tried to read this book and actually hoped that I would like it, yeah, nah. I got up to page 42 and was like <i>there are better books out there than me slogging through the next 700 pages and can use my time better doing anything else</i>. So that’s what I did and dropped this book entirely. <br /><br />I first heard about this book when I picked up <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/79203.Spangle" title="Spangle by Gary Jennings" rel="nofollow noopener"> Spangle</a> earlier this year and ended up really liking it and saw that the author had a much more popular book out there called Aztec. This was that book. I’m not giving it a rating since I read so very little of the book and maybe it gets better, I dunno, but don’t really want to find out, so no rating, just a flat out DNF. <br /><br />The first thing I was thrown off by, the small text and the massive paragraphs that would have meant that this book would have taken forever to read. Granted, I’ve read loads of books with very small text, massive series such as Malazan Book of the Fallen and The Wheel of Time spring to mind. How about War and Peace, or Les Misérables? I’m not new to a small font or large descriptive paragraphs describing absolutely everything. Rather, there are parts of this book that reads like a history text book. It follows this guy as he mentions the geography of the region and all the traditions, religions, sacrifices, etc. World building, great! Info dumping to the scale it makes you feel like you are reading <i>History of the Aztec Empire 101</i>, not so great. <br /><br />Next up, this book was not what I was expecting at all. Instead of just being the first person perspective of a character, it is in fact the first person perspective of a guy in his sixties telling a story to Spanish Scribes which takes out the joy of discovery and adventure and feels like a slog. Not to mention the main character talking to invisible people that we know nothing about at random points throughout the book. To the reader, it made me feel like he was talking to a wall, or himself and massively detracted from the story, which was slow and chunky enough at this point.<br /><br />School teachers tell you to start your stories with a bang, not all books do this. It is not necessary at all to start with a bang, yet, still start with something that might at least excite the reader in the least, to keep it interesting. Instead, it starts with a bunch of court documents that largely have nothing to do with the story the guy is trying to tell. The long documents felt like reading essays and instead of going straight into the story, the main character then rambles on about his childhood and every single bit of random information about the Aztec Empire that he encountered. The author did a lot of research, that much is clear, but telling me about the world that I could obtain from a textbook instead did not draw me into the novel. In fact, Invicta has an awesome video on YouTube about growing up in the Aztec Empire, so how much better would it have been if he showed us the world instead, with descriptions, delicious smells and the hardness of life. I much prefer a story that shows me the world compared to telling me about the world.<br /><br />If I can rant that much from just 42 pages of this book, I’m afraid what reading the remainder of the book will do to me. No rating</span>
  <a data-text-id="17269285727826228318" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


